{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ae6051d2-5281-46e3-a472-1cea5cb13594","content":"You don't need the SDK. Install `dotnet-trace` as a **global tool** using just the .NET runtime, or grab the standalone binary:\n\n### Option 1 – Install as a global tool\n```bash\n# Inside the container (requires the .NET SDK *CLI* but not the full SDK):\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n### Option 2 – Download the standalone package (no SDK needed)\n```bash\n# Download the self-contained dotnet-trace for linux-x64\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### Collect the CPU trace\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n./dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU-sampling trace (default profile is cpu-sampling)\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can copy out (`docker cp`) and open in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`--format speedscope`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94b0430a-6396-4ad0-8cb4-f9307172764d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU. This is a general knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling — I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":376,"requestId":"7842:8A8EB:1D244B9:2071E65:69FA9919"},"id":"5a906ef0-e15f-4afb-907f-b9c28bdc8b1d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:28:04.500Z","parentId":"7b19951e-987f-4b41-9a6a-4ae0fe474f23"}
